  "text": "Phagocytosis of apoptotic cells has been suggested to play a potential role in the induction of immune tolerance. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Defective apoptotic cell phagocytosis in Mfge8 Ϫ/Ϫ mice could have contributed to the proimmunoinflammatory phenotype of these animals by altering the natural regulatory T-cell function that controls immune homeostasis. We therefore assessed the proliferative potential of CD4 ϩ cells. Using in vivo bromodeoxyuridine staining, we found similar levels of CD4 ϩ proliferation but increased CD69 expression ( Figure 7A ) in Mfge8 Ϫ/Ϫ compared with Mfge8 ϩ/ϩ chimeras, which suggests enhanced T-cell activation. Effector CD4 ϩ CD25 Ϫ cells purified from chimeric Mfge8 Ϫ/Ϫ mice showed reduced in vitro proliferation compared with chimeric Mfge8 ϩ/ϩ mice, after CD3 stimulation in the presence of CD11c ϩ dendritic cells ( Figure 8A , CD25 Ϫ alone). Such reduction in effector T-cell proliferation in vitro has been reported previously in mice with alteration in immune regulation and increased T-cell activation. [CITATION_3] The percentage of CD4 ϩ CD25 ϩ cells, determined in spleens and lymph nodes, was similar between chimeric Mfge8 Ϫ/Ϫ and Mfge8 ϩ/ϩ mice ( Figure 7B ). Protein and mRNA expression levels of Foxp3, a transcription factor specific for the regulatory T-cell lineage, were comparable between the 2 groups of mice ( Figure 7C and 7D) . Remarkably, however, CD4 ϩ CD25 ϩ cells purified from chimeric Mfge8 Ϫ/Ϫ mice after 8 to 10 weeks of high-fat diet failed to inhibit the proliferation of effector CD4 ϩ CD25 -cells ( Figure 8A and 8B). This alteration was observed in 4 of 5 different experiments with male or female Mfge8 Ϫ/Ϫ mice but was never observed in 5 different experiments with male or female Mfge8 ϩ/ϩ mice (2 to 3 mice per group in each experiment). In addition, a significant alteration in suppressive T-cell function was observed in pure nonatherosclerotic Mfge8 Ϫ/Ϫ mice compared with wild-type controls (percent inhibition of T-cell proliferation at 1:8 ratio, Ϫ/Ϫ dendritic cells ( Figure 8D ). These results strongly suggest a dendritic cell-dependent alteration in regulatory T-cell suppressive potential in the absence of Mfge8, which is an ",
